  "text": "The problem of counting subgraphs is one of the fundamental questions in algorithm design, and has various applications in analyzing the clustering and transitivity coefficients of networks, uncovering structural information of graphs that model biological systems, and designing graph databases. While the exact counting of subgraphs of constant size is polynomial-time solvable, traditional algorithms need to store the whole graph and compute the solution in an off-line fashion, which is not practical even for graphs of medium size. A modern way to deal with this problem is to design algorithms in the streaming setting, where the edges of the underlying graph come sequentially in an arbitrary order, and algorithms with sub-linear space are required to approximately count the number of occurrences of certain subgraphs. Since the first streaming algorithm by Bar-Yossef et al. [CITATION_1] , this problem has received much attention in recent years [2-4, 6, 7, 11, 12, 14] .",
